      "writtenOn": "2026-06-30T03:34:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The issue was observed while running a local TCP session benchmark. The benchmark\ncompleted, but the server side reported \"PAWS check failed\" drops in show errors\n(PAWS \u003d Protection Against Wrapped Sequence numbers, the TCP timestamp check).\n\nI agree active open is the currently observed path where timestamps from\ndifferent workers are compared. However, I think the root issue is more general:\nTCP TSval is protocol-visible per-connection state, but today it is derived from\nworker-local cached vlib time. If a connection\u0027s packet generation path crosses\nworkers, TSval can go backwards for that connection.\n\nThis change keeps session/transport time in the existing vlib-time form, but\nalso caches the raw CPU sample taken at the same update point. TCP derives TSval\nfrom that process-wide CPU epoch, so TSval is comparable across workers without\nadding a second independent time sampling path.\n\nIf this is considered too broad for the observed failure mode, I can rework it\ninto a narrower active-open-only fix that preserves TSval monotonicity when the\nhalf-open connection moves to the established worker.",
      "parentUuid": "3aa1a165_05e9ebdd",
      "revId": "424d2f91aa014060343c18289238695ff39eefec",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f8332f43_f66b29bf",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 193
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-06-30T04:08:01Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I would like to understand more about that paws check failure. If handshake acks are going backwards with the tsval, that is definitely wrong. Having said that, vpp should keep workers time in sync. We\u0027ve had some changes in that area and I think we have an issue with main vs worker time differences (as opposed to across workers) but \n\nRegarding your second point, connections (and sessions) are pinned to workers. In fact, we drop packets that are received on the wrong thread. So the only scenario where we could have a genuine issue is the one above, i.e., first worker sends syn, syn-ack pins the established connection on another worker and now that worker\u0027s time goes backwards and the ack leads to a paws error. Would it be possible for you to check if this is what happens or just a misclassified paws because of port reuse?\n\nSo yes, if this is confirmed, we should look into ways of guaranteeing tsval monotonicity.",
      "parentUuid": "7901461e_87feec2a",
      "revId": "424d2f91aa014060343c18289238695ff39eefec",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1769c1bf_4f652785",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
